<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
In much of its range this species is easily recognised by its creamy-white flowers arranged in subumbellate cymes. However it can only be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea reticulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the larger sepals and corolla and some specimens can be difficult to assign, particularly from the Brasilia area. There is a case, therefore, for treating these two species as subspecies but we are reluctant to make this decision. Although 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. reticulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is always glabrous or minutely scabridulous-puberulent, the leaves of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="saopaulista">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. saopaulista</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are commonly densely pubescent or even tomentose, a state never seen in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. reticulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and mere size is not, therefore, the only distinguishing feature between the two species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
